
== Eclipse Sleak

	
		_Eclipse Sleak_
		monitors the creation and disposal of SWT graphics
		resources. Get it from the
		<ulink
			url="http://www.eclipse.org/swt/tools.php">
			SWT Development Tools
		or install the Eclipse Plugin via the
		<ulink
			url="http://www.eclipse.org/swt/updatesite.php">
			SWT Tools Update Sites
		.
	

	
		To
		activate
		Sleak, you can use the
		_Tracing_
		tab in your Eclipse runtime configuration.
	

	
		<mediaobject>
			<imageobject>
				<imagedata fileref="images/sleaktrace10.png"/>
			</imageobject>
			<textobject>
				<phrase></phrase>
			</textobject>
		</mediaobject>
	

	
		<mediaobject>
			<imageobject>
				<imagedata fileref="images/sleaktrace20.png"/>
			</imageobject>
			<textobject>
				<phrase></phrase>
			</textobject>
		</mediaobject>
	

	
		Alternatively you can also activate it for your Eclipse IDE. For
		this
		you have to start Eclipse with the
		_-debug_
		option from the command
		line. You also need to create a
		_.options_
		file in the Eclipse installation directory with the following entries.
	
	
		<programlisting language="text">
			<xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"
				parse="text" href="./examples/sleak/options.txt" />
		</programlisting>
	

	
		If you start your Eclipse IDE, you find the
		_Sleak_
		view
		under
		menu:
			<guimenu>Window</guimenu>
			<guisubmenu>Show View</guisubmenu>
			<guisubmenu>Other ...</guisubmenu>
			<guisubmenu>SWT Tools</guisubmenu>
			<guisubmenu>Sleak</guisubmenu>
		</menuchoice>
		.`
	

	
		_Sleak_
		allows you to take a snapshot and create a diff. Clicking on
		_Stacktrace_
		gives you the stacktrace in which the resource was allocated.
	


